{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3c9e7dd-4f8c-4022-9e90-131f86381de4","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports when a process crashes. Look in these locations:\n\n1. **User-level crash reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level crash reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\n**To get a core dump** instead, run before launching your app:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCore files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash reports contain the crashed thread's backtrace, register state, and loaded images — often enough to start triaging without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"560df17b-65a7-42fa-99a1-b06d82f459ea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app crash on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting — I can answer directly.","outputTokens":270},"id":"7c44a126-b335-4246-a232-d041bcf63835","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:01:00.043Z","parentId":"4b401e27-e85f-4420-bd7e-e0d5a5e2cc7a"}
